This week, I had the honor of meeting with the Tragedy Assistance Program for Survivors (TAPS) to discuss how we can better support the families of our fallen service members. 

In Florida’s 20th District, we are proud of our military families and committed to ensuring they receive the care and resources they deserve. Their sacrifice will never be forgotten.

I was honored to open Africa Diaspora Day on the Hill, where I shared how I’ve been hosting meetings to teach our district how to do business with Africa.

Doing business with Africa and the Caribbean can grow our local economy, create jobs, and strengthen ties between the U.S. and the diaspora.

By supporting efforts like AIDA and encouraging partnerships with African businesses, we’re helping District 20 tap into new opportunities right now and for the future.

95% of malaria deaths occur in Africa, resulting in profound loss of life. This crisis poses a significant threat to global health and demands urgent attention.

Reducing funding is not only poor policy but also detrimental to global security.

My resolution aims to strengthen Africa’s capacity to detect and respond to public health emergencies promptly.

Investing in Africa’s health is an investment in the safety of the American people.

Each year, diaspora communities send over $100 billion to Africa and the Caribbean, and over $200 billion globally. This is untapped power. 

Diaspora finance is not a funding gap to be filled—it is a competitive advantage to be unleashed. 

It’s time for U.S. policy to recognize diaspora capital as a strategic asset. It fuels development, strengthens communities, and advances our soft power.

My amendment lays the foundation for unlocking capital, turning remittances into investment, fueling industrial growth, and deepening trust between the U.S., Africa, and Caribbean nations.

Haiti's instability affects the United States every day. Yet, the decision to dismantle the Office of Haiti Affairs was made without a clear strategy.

We must ensure that Haiti receives the attention it rightfully deserves. A stable Haiti means a more stable United States.

I remain committed to restoring the focus and urgency that the Haitian crisis demands.

I urge bipartisan support for my amendment.

I had a very productive meeting with the International Franchise Association (IFA) to discuss opportunities and challenges facing franchise businesses in our district. 

Supporting local entrepreneurs and small business owners is key to driving economic growth and job creation in our communities. 

I look forward to working together to ensure our district continues to thrive.

On Constitution and Citizenship Day, we honor the living document that safeguards our freedoms and strengthens our democracy.

I'm committed to upholding these values by fighting for the rights, opportunities, and voices of every constituent I serve.

Together, we protect the promise of a more perfect union.

The Veterans Readiness and Employment Program Integrity Act is a win for our veterans. They deserve timely, effective support as they transition to civilian life, and this bill helps hold the VA accountable.

I’m proud to share it has passed the House. Co-led with Rep. Ciscomani (R-AZ), this bipartisan bill increases transparency to the VA’s VR&E program.

I’ll keep working to get it signed into law.

I met with Tom Krause, CEO of Cloud Software, and his team to discuss how we can drive growth and innovation in our district’s tech economy. Their expertise will help create new jobs, improve skills training, and attract investment to benefit our community.

I’m committed to advancing policies that create opportunities for all.

Each Sunday, I look forward to beginning the week by speaking with congregations across South Florida.

Sharing legislative updates gives us the opportunity to come together not just in worship, but in gratitude for what we've achieved and in hope for what lies ahead.

I'm honored to stand with you and to be reminded of the strength we find in unity, purpose, and prayer.

It was an honor to celebrate 10 years of @BRCASTRONG, a grassroots powerhouse that has turned pain into purpose and compassion into action. 

From free pre-mastectomy care packages to life-saving screenings in underserved communities, their work empowers, uplifts, and changes lives. Here's to a decade of strength, resilience, and impact, and to the years ahead.

I had the honor of joining the National Congress of Black Women for their High Tea.

I am proud to stand with leaders who uplift communities, empower future generations, and advocate for justice. 

Together, we are shaping a future built on equity and lasting change. https://t.co/ufigtJloaP

It was an honor to join ICNA Relief, an organization that exemplifies compassion, service, and hope. In times of crisis, from food insecurity to natural disasters, you show up without hesitation, restoring dignity and meeting people where they are. Thank you for being the hands and heart of service. 

Together, we share a vision where no child goes hungry, no mother suffers in silence, and no neighbor is left behind.

I had a productive meeting this afternoon with Florida Medical Center.

I’m grateful for their leadership and commitment to our community. Together, we’ll continue working to expand access, improve outcomes, and build a healthier future for everyone in our District. https://t.co/DYY9CZHFRg

I’m so proud to stand with David Perez, our Angels in Adoption honoree.

David’s heart for families shows the true spirit of District 20–looking out for each other and lifting each other up.

This award is a win for him and for all of us who believe every child deserves love and a strong future.

No one should have to live in fear of being gunned down or threatened while at school, church, work, or in their own communities.

Read the full statement at the link in bio. https://t.co/dFmGGqpZx0

Fighting for working-class families in my district is my top priority. I’m honored to join our union to share legislative remarks on the issues that matter most.

Together, we’re building a future where every family has the opportunity to thrive. https://t.co/GZcI9evPtU

Today, we honor the lives lost, the heroes who rose, and the resilience of our nation. This tragedy struck our nation 24 years ago, and the scars of terrorism still linger. 

We will never forget. 

Today, we continue to fight to protect our homeland against terrorism—both foreign and domestic. While the day is heavy, we find strength in unity, compassion, and the enduring spirit of the American people.

Political violence has no place in our nation, and it never will. The tragic loss of Charlie Kirk’s life to political violence is a sobering reminder of the urgent need to confront these threats with unity and resolve. 

We must condemn political violence in every form, and those responsible must be held fully accountable under the law.

I was honored to join the American Jewish Committee in commemorating the anniversary of the Abraham Accords. These historic agreements have transformed the Middle East, fostering unprecedented trade, innovation, and cultural exchange.

We must continue to lead and expand this progress to build lasting peace and opportunity.

We’ve dedicated our lives to supporting our families, strengthening our communities, and building a better future. We all deserve to be treated with dignity and respect.

Join me this Sunday for an important conversation about protecting immigration, Food Assistance, and Medicaid to ensure the benefits and safety we’ve earned are never taken away.

We deserve better, and together, we will make it happen.

It was an honor to speak at @gwlaw during their Haiti Academic Conference about the path forward for Haiti.

As we look to rebuild and strengthen the nation, we must invest in the next generation of leaders.

Their vision, resilience, and commitment will be the driving force behind a stable and prosperous future for Haiti.

Veterans deserve comprehensive healthcare, including full access to reproductive services.

I’m proud to stand in solidarity with my colleagues today in defense of reproductive freedom for our veterans.

We cannot allow a rollback of critical care and basic rights.

No exceptions.

The #FL20 Mobile Office is hitting the road!

Check out our upcoming stops—we’re bringing services directly to your community.

Need help with Social Security, immigration, or another federal issue? We’re here to assist you.

On this #LaborDay, we honor the hardworking men and women who have built and continue to sustain our great nation. Today, we celebrate their contributions and reaffirm our commitment to fight for fair wages, safe working conditions, and the dignity every worker deserves. https://t.co/mZsTiSO91O

Happy National Senior Citizens Day! Today we celebrate the wisdom, resilience, and contributions of our seniors who have paved the way for future generations. 

I will never stop fighting for you and remain committed to ensuring every senior in our community can age with dignity, security, and joy.

For 6 months, Republicans have attacked @DeptVetAffairs and DOGE, undermining the very watchdog protecting veterans’ care.

Now, OIG reports 4,434 severe staffing shortages, a 50% spike.

These attacks aren’t about “accountability.” They’re about dismantling VA. 

We won’t let them.
https://t.co/TtXphWjuOT

I joined 84 of my colleagues, led by @USRepKCastor and @RepPaulTonko, in urging @EPA to reject the reckless rollback of carbon pollution standards for power plants. 

Our communities deserve clean air and a safe climate, and I’ll keep fighting for both. 
https://t.co/xIa2wmwpgb

On Monday, I held a Townhall with South Florida’s medical community to discuss how Medicaid cuts impact patient care.

This was about listening to our seniors, veterans, working families, and everyone who has helped build this country.

I’m fighting to protect Medicaid, Food Assistance, and Social Security because these programs aren’t just numbers in a budget, they’re lifelines.

You’ve paid in. You’ve done everything right. You deserve to be rewarded, not punished.

We will not let cuts, red tape, or political games take away what you’ve earned. 

Together, we’ll keep fighting for a stronger, fairer future.

We’re Going LIVE! 🚨

Tomorrow, I’m hitting the road for my Black Business Month Tour, spotlighting the power, resilience, and brilliance of Black-owned businesses in our community.

✅ Step behind the scenes
✅ Hear powerful stories from local entrepreneurs
✅ See how we’re building lasting economic power

This is more than a tour. It’s a movement. 

Tune in and be part of the change.

I had a wonderful time kicking off the school year with a warm First Day Greeting at Weleby Elementary.

Seeing the dedication of the staff, the passion of the teachers, and the bright smiles of the students reminds me why my work is so meaningful.

Here’s to a fantastic school year ahead!

Florida tourism already brings in over $125 billion/year, supports 2 million jobs, and contributes nearly $35 billion in taxes annually. 
 
Measures deterring visitors or trade would have massive ripple effects. This is a bad idea. 
https://t.co/DlCMVG0QTE

On #PurpleHeartDay, we honor the brave men and women who’ve sacrificed for our nation. 

As we remember their service, we remain committed to protecting and supporting our veterans now more than ever. https://t.co/FRTK48ANZo

Thanks to House Republicans, health insurance premiums are set to spike.

If they let ACA tax credits expire, 4M Floridians could see premiums jump from $588 to $1,116/year — plus a $470 hike in FL-20 from the Republicans’ Big Ugly Bill.

Demand Senate Republicans to take action. The American people are waiting and cannot afford delays.

I spoke with @nbc6 following last week’s hearing, where I repeatedly asked: What is the strategy?

When it comes to Haiti and TPS holders, we need answers and action. If we don’t act with urgency and compassion, we risk turning our backs on families who have built their lives here and on a nation that needs real partnership—not abandonment.

U.S. weapons must stop fueling the violence in Haiti. That’s why @RepGregoryMeeks and I led our colleagues in demanding urgent action to halt the illegal flow of firearms from our shores to Haitian gangs. 

Lives are being lost. 
 
The time to act is now. https://t.co/DGBMIHOk9H

Thanks to a letter led by @RepLoisFrankel and me, the administration is finally taking action to lower the cost of anti-obesity medications for Americans. 

This is a strong first step, but more action is needed.
https://t.co/7OuccI4n6L

A U.S. citizen disappeared by ICE.
 
This is exactly why I continue to sound the alarm.
 
When even American citizens are being targeted, we must ask: who’s really safe?
 
This isn’t just about immigration. It’s about justice, due process, and protecting our rights here at home.
 
We need urgent reform now.
https://t.co/ei2QBYIohl

This week, I visited Holy Cross New Family Health Center and spoke with frontline healthcare workers about the challenges and opportunities in Medicare and Medicaid.

These programs are vital to millions, and strengthening them means ensuring everyone has access to quality, affordable care when they need it most.

Healthcare shouldn’t be a privilege. You deserve better, and I’m committed to making that a reality.

Today marks 60 years of Medicare and Medicaid—programs that are not a handout, but a lifeline for millions. These vital services protect our health, our dignity, and our future. 

We must stand firm in defending them and ensure they continue to serve those who need them most, now and for generations to come.

This weekend's announcement that Israel would allow airdrops and open humanitarian corridors — alongside Arab partners — is long overdue. It is a necessary step, but much more must be done.

RSVP here: https://t.co/3zPjcwgPm3 

By empowering these communities, we can move beyond outdated models of foreign aid and embrace a future built on dignity, mutual investment, and shared prosperity.

I hope to see you there.

Yesterday at Eglise Baptiste Saphir Tabernacle De L’Evangile, I had the honor of speaking with the community and sharing a message of hope and resilience.

I’m continuing the fight to:
✅ Stop ICE detention centers near our Everglades
✅ Lower housing costs
✅ Expand access to healthcare
✅ Protect dignity in every part of our lives

To every TPS holder: You belong here. This is your home.

We’re not just surviving — we’re rising. Because we know that when we fight, we win.

It was an honor to attend the 4th Annual Bahamas Diaspora Independence Awards Dinner in celebration of 52 years of nationhood and the vital contributions of the Bahamian diaspora. 

Congratulations to this year’s awardees. 

Your dedication and impact are truly inspiring. Together, let us continue building a brighter future for all.

Does this Administration have a Haiti strategy? That remains to be seen.

When it comes to Haiti, that sounds more like a slogan than a strategy.

They want to eliminate the Office of Haitian Affairs at the State Department without any contingency plan. 

I’ll work with anyone to ensure this critical office remains in place and operating at full capacity.

Protecting our health and safety must be the top priority. Using radioactive materials like phosphogypsum in our roads puts families and our future at risk.
 
That’s why I’m proud to join @RepMaxwellFrost to reintroduce the No Radioactive Roads Act, because every Floridian deserves safe, toxin-free communities.

My amendment doesn’t restrict our veterans—it empowers them.

It strengthens the support they receive, but instead, we’re turning a blind eye to what’s happening in the VA and in our communities.
 
We have a responsibility to act, to give our veterans the care, structure, and specialized support they’ve earned through their service. 
 
They have unique needs, and they deserve a system designed to meet them.
 
Pass my amendment. Let’s stand with those who’ve served.

House Republicans shut down Congress for over a month to avoid a vote on releasing the Epstein Files.

While they protect the elite, 27.6 million people are being trafficked worldwide, and thousands of children go missing in the U.S. every year.

Meanwhile, Americans are struggling to afford groceries, gas, and rent. Inflation is crushing working families—and Congress refuses to act.

House Democrats are demanding answers and accountability. The truth can’t wait.

Inflation is out of control. Gas, groceries, and rent keep going up, and working families are paying the price.
 
While you struggle to make ends meet, House Republicans shut down Congress instead of showing up to vote on your future.
 
No action on relief. Just more distractions.

Thanks to our collective advocacy, Temporary Protected Status (TPS) has been extended through February 2026, marking a major legal victory for our communities.

But our fight isn’t over. Now, we must continue pushing for permanent protections.

Join me tomorrow, Wednesday, July 23, at 6:00 PM EST for my Tele-Townhall on Securing Stability: What Comes Next for TPS?

RSVP here: https://t.co/4ARiGSQpuG

Together, we can turn this temporary relief into lasting security.

I hope to see you there.

On Sunday at New Hope Baptist Church, I had the honor of standing with our community and sharing a message of hope and resilience.

I spoke about a recent legal victory that reaffirms the power of collective action—and my ongoing commitment to building a future where every family is treated with dignity and respect.

One thing is clear: when we come together and fight for what’s right, we win.

As we wrap up another week in Congress and look ahead, I'm filled with hope and gratitude for the strength of our community.

Through every challenge, we've proven that when we stand together, united in purpose and guided by compassion, we are unstoppable.

The road ahead may not always be easy, but together, we will build a future that is more just, more inclusive, and full of opportunity for all.

I spoke with @nbc6 about the big court win for our Haitian community. We fought for the expansion of TPS, and we won. Our community showed up, stood strong, and made this happen.

As the Congresswoman for South Florida, where more TPS holders live than anywhere else in the country, I know how much this means. This win helps families stay together, work, and live without fear.

This was more than just a court case. It was about doing what’s right and recognizing the crisis in Haiti.

And we’re not stopping here. I will keep fighting for permanent protections and real change for our people.

It was an honor to join esteemed leaders at the Diplomatic Dinner in celebration of The Bahamas' 52nd Independence Anniversary and the commemoration of 52 years of the Caribbean Community’s establishment.

I stressed the importance of policies that truly represent all Americans, with particular attention to the Global Black Diaspora, and called for expanded economic opportunities throughout the Caribbean.

Together, we have a responsibility to build a future defined by shared prosperity, unity, and progress.

This is not just a policy decision—it is a hard-fought legal victory for the Haitian community and all who have stood in defense of our immigrant families. 

The court’s ruling makes clear what we have always known: TPS holders deserve stability, protection, and respect, not political games or legal uncertainty. 
 
Read the full statement at the link in bio.

Following a major court ruling and months of advocacy, Rep. Cherfilus-McCormick calls the halt to Haitian TPS deportations a legal victory—and a crucial step toward lasting dignity, protection, and meaningful immigration reform for Haitian families and immigrant communities nationwide.
 
Read the full statement at the link in bio.

Courageous. Selfless. Resilient—these are just a few words that describe Nelson Mandela and the profound impact he had and continues to have on the world.

His legacy knows no bounds. May we honor his memory by committing to a future led by kindness, shaped by impact, and forged through hope.

I spoke with @usatoday about the harmful legacy of stigmatizing Haitian Americans.

Let me be clear: Haiti is not a “savage” nation. That language is steeped in ignorance and erases the truth about our people’s resilience, strength, and historic contributions.

Haitian Americans, like so many African and immigrant communities, have helped build this country and continue to power our economy. From small businesses to essential services, we are not outsiders. We are vital to America’s success.

We deserve dignity, respect, and the opportunity to thrive, just like anyone who calls this country home.

I’m proud to be an original cosponsor of the No Cages in the Everglades Act. No one—absolutely no one—should be subjected to harsh or degrading conditions.
 
This is America: the land of the free, not the land of the confined. https://t.co/nVIPZtohWk

Adequate staffing and expertise in fragile regions like Syria are critical. As Ranking Member of the Middle East and North Africa Subcommittee, I remain committed to ensuring we continue moving forward—not backward.
 
Efficient passport and visa processing, renewed hope in vulnerable communities, and a strong diplomatic presence are essential to maintaining regional stability. We must stay on an upward trajectory.

They stood up for us. Now it is our turn to stand with them, with action, with investment, and with unwavering support.
 
When you cut the VA, you are not just cutting services. You are cutting the very values America is built on.

It was an honor to meet with the Prime Minister of Haiti, Mr. Alix Didier Fils-Aimé. Our conversation was productive, reaffirming our shared values and our commitment to the security of the Haitian people.

I remain committed to working alongside Prime Minister Fils-Aimé and my colleagues to help Haiti build a more stable, secure, and prosperous future.

Community care is vital for our veterans, but long-term stability demands bipartisan action.
 
We need timely, accurate information to protect patients and ensure veterans can retire with dignity.
 
Homecare agencies are sounding the alarm about Medicaid cuts. The transition process must support patients at every step.

Mental illness knows no boundaries.

We must act now to lower costs and save lives.

I ended the 4th of July weekend with a beautiful evening of worship at Bethel Evangelical Baptist Church. 

It was a true honor to recognize and celebrate Grande Croisade Évangélique and the Haitian Baptist Pastors Fellowship.

Your unwavering commitment to this community is intangible. Thank you for all that you do!

On Saturday, I stood with immigrant families and advocates outside the Broward Transitional Center to honor the memory of Marie Ange Blaise—and the many others who have died in ICE custody or suffered under a broken immigration system.

From her tragic death last year to the rushed construction of the “Alligator Alcatraz” facility in the Everglades, it’s clear: this system prioritizes cruelty over care.

It’s time to expand TPS, end racist immigration policies, and protect the people who help build this country every day.

Today, I stood with immigrant families and advocates to call for real change. As the proud daughter of Haitian immigrants, I know the strength and sacrifice our communities bring to this country.

We gathered not in silence—but in strength. Not in fear—but in faith.

It’s time to expand TPS, open doors to humanitarian parole, end racist travel bans, and stop deporting working-class immigrants who are the backbone of this nation.

Earlier today on @MSNBC, I said it plainly: This Big Ugly Bill won’t be remembered for what it builds—but for what it destroys.

It forces families to reverify every six months, with no new funding to manage the burden.

The result? Delays. Denials. Devastation.

Some parts may sound good—but they quietly expire in 2028.

The harm? Permanent.

If we truly want to make life better for our constituents, we need real, bipartisan solutions—not cuts disguised as reform.

As we observe Immigrant Heritage Month and Caribbean American Heritage Month, we proudly honor the strength and resilience of those who shape the very fabric of our nation.

It is with great honor that I present this proclamation recognizing Dr. Solanges Vivens. Your unwavering dedication and exceptional contributions inspire us all. Thank you for everything you do.

This Immigrant Heritage Month and Caribbean American Heritage Month, we’re reminded that diversity is our strength and unity is our power.

Today, I’m proud to honor Dr. Solanges Vivens, a Haitian American who transformed the landscape of long-term care—proving that with unwavering faith, even the highest mountains can be moved.
